<section class="section">
  <div class="wrap wrap--narrow">
    <div class="faq">
      <details class="faq__item" open>
        <summary>What is RCPD?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            RCPD stands for Retrograde Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction. It's a condition where the
            cricopharyngeus muscle in the throat fails to relax properly, preventing a natural
            burp. This can cause chronic bloating, discomfort, and gurgling noises as trapped
            air can't escape.
          </p>
          <figure class="figure">
            <div class="figure__pair">
              <img src="/assets/img/without-rcpd.png" alt="Anatomy of a normal burp, where the cricopharyngeus relaxes to release air" loading="lazy" width="403" height="253">
              <img src="/assets/img/with-rcpd.png" alt="Anatomy of RCPD, where the cricopharyngeus stays tight and traps air" loading="lazy" width="526" height="518">
            </div>
            <figcaption class="figure-note">
              Illustrations by
              <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/natalie_uic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">u/natalie_uic</a>.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What causes RCPD, and is it common?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            The exact cause isn't fully understood. In RCPD the cricopharyngeus muscle &mdash; the
            upper esophageal sphincter &mdash; doesn't relax to vent swallowed air the way it should,
            so gas builds up instead of being released as a burp. For most people it appears to be a
            lifelong trait, and many recall never having been able to burp. It's thought to be more
            common than once believed but remains widely under-recognized, so people often go years
            without a name for their symptoms.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What are the common signs and symptoms?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <ul class="stack">
            <li>Inability to burp, or extreme difficulty burping</li>
            <li>Frequent gurgling, rumbling, or squeaking noises in the throat or upper chest</li>
            <li>Bloating, chest pressure, or discomfort after meals or carbonated drinks</li>
            <li>Excessive flatulence</li>
            <li>Occasional relief through passing gas, &ldquo;air-vomiting,&rdquo; or lying down</li>
            <li>Social or dietary changes to avoid triggers like carbonated beverages</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>How is RCPD diagnosed?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            RCPD is often recognized from its distinctive symptom pattern &mdash; chiefly a lifelong
            inability to burp combined with gurgling, bloating, and excess gas. Standard tests such as
            endoscopy or a barium swallow usually come back normal, which is part of why it's
            frequently missed or mistaken for reflux, IBS, or aerophagia. Some specialists use
            high-resolution esophageal manometry to help confirm it. A laryngologist familiar with
            RCPD is best placed to make the call.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>Is RCPD dangerous or life-threatening?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            RCPD is not considered life-threatening, but it can significantly affect quality of
            life. Chronic discomfort, anxiety, and lifestyle changes are common. In some cases
            ongoing strain may lead to secondary issues, so a professional evaluation is
            recommended if symptoms persist.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What treatment options are available?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <ul class="stack">
            <li><strong>Botox injection:</strong> the most established and effective treatment. It relaxes the cricopharyngeus so trapped air can finally escape as a burp. Reported success rates are high &mdash; frequently around 90% &mdash; and for many people a single injection brings lasting relief.</li>
            <li><strong>Cricopharyngeal myotomy:</strong> a surgical option that partially divides the muscle, sometimes considered when Botox doesn't provide a durable benefit.</li>
            <li><strong>Self-help measures:</strong> some people find partial relief from posture changes, certain exercises, or limiting carbonation &mdash; but these manage symptoms rather than correct the underlying problem.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What does the Botox injection do?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            For RCPD, a botulinum toxin (Botox) injection relaxes the cricopharyngeus muscle in
            the upper esophageal sphincter. That muscle is supposed to relax to let gas escape as
            a burp, but in RCPD it stays overly tight &mdash; trapping air and causing bloating,
            discomfort, and gurgling. Relaxing it lets people burp, often for the first time.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>Does the treatment last, or does it wear off?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            This is one of the more reassuring parts of RCPD treatment. Although Botox itself wears
            off over a few months, many people keep the ability to burp long after it fades &mdash;
            the reflex seems to &ldquo;re-learn&rdquo; itself, and for a large share of patients the
            benefit is durable or even permanent. A minority need a second injection, and a few
            choose a myotomy for a more permanent fix.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What should I do if I suspect I have RCPD?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <ul class="stack">
            <li>Document your symptoms, including triggers and how often they happen.</li>
            <li>Consult a specialist &mdash; ideally a laryngologist (a throat-focused ENT).</li>
            <li>Discuss treatment options; early intervention can help manage symptoms.</li>
          </ul>
          <p><a class="arrow" href="/find-a-doctor.html">Find a doctor near you &rarr;</a></p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What is &ldquo;air-vomiting&rdquo;?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            Air-vomiting (sometimes &ldquo;air-puking&rdquo;) is the forced expulsion of trapped
            air from the stomach or esophagus. It mimics vomiting without bringing up any solids
            or liquids, and some people with RCPD use it to relieve discomfort.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What is emetophobia?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            Emetophobia is an intense fear of vomiting, seeing vomit, or feeling nauseous. RCPD
            can trigger or worsen it, since trapped gas can cause sensations similar to nausea
            and increase anxiety about vomiting.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq__item">
        <summary>What is an ENT doctor?</summary>
        <div class="faq__body">
          <p>
            An ENT (Ear, Nose, and Throat) doctor, also called an otolaryngologist, diagnoses and
            treats conditions of the ears, nose, throat, and related head-and-neck structures. A
            <em>laryngologist</em> &mdash; an ENT focused on the voice box and swallowing &mdash;
            is the primary specialist for treating RCPD.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
